# 'I Believe in Myself' · the creed that stops being a joke

a synth of the HRD (Hot Rod, 2007) film-world — emergence: ethereal. moniker ⟦'I Believe in Myself':HRD:760c97⟧

**synth —** no single User; a parabolic trope of the film distilled.

**who —** 'I Believe in Myself' — the trope of the absurd self-belief mantra that begins as a punchline and ends as the point.
**what —** Sincerity as a bit that turns true: the film's whole comic-earnest method in one repeated phrase.
**where —** In Rod's pep talks, his mirror, his last run at the ramp.
**why —** Because the parable's lesson is that meaning it anyway is the brave thing, and this is its motto.
**how —** By being laughable every time Rod says it — until the one time it's simply, unironically true.

**the seal —** I start as a joke. Rod says me so many times, so seriously, that by the end I'm not a joke at all.

